msgid "What is the output hash?"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"The output hash is a SHA-256 fingerprint computed when a validation run "
"completes. It covers the stable validation context and the final run "
"outcome, creating a tamper-evident seal. If any covered field were modified "
"after completion, the hash would no longer match."
msgstr ""

msgid "Fields included"
msgstr ""

msgid "The workflow or workflow-hash context used to interpret the run"
msgstr ""

msgid "Unique identifier of the run"
msgstr "Identifiant unique de l’exécution"

msgid "Final status (e.g. Succeeded, Failed)"
msgstr ""

msgid "When the run started (ISO 8601 UTC)"
msgstr ""

msgid "When the run completed (ISO 8601 UTC)"
msgstr ""

msgid "Run duration in milliseconds"
msgstr ""

msgid "Number of error-severity findings"
msgstr ""

msgid "Number of warning-severity findings"
msgstr ""

msgid "Number of info-severity findings"
msgstr ""

msgid "Total finding count"
msgstr "Nombre total de constats"

msgid "How it works"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Validibot serializes the covered fields into a deterministic JSON document, "
"hashes that document with SHA-256, and stores the resulting 64-character "
"digest on the run record. Installations with signed credentials enabled use "
"the stricter workflow-centered Layer 3 contract from Validibot Pro; "
"community installs fall back to the built-in host contract. In both cases, "
"the digest helps reveal whether the run record was changed after completion."
msgstr ""

msgid "What the SHACL validator does"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"The SHACL validator checks an RDF submission against one or more SHACL shape "
"files. It is the right validator for Turtle, JSON-LD, RDF/XML, N-Triples, "
"and N-Quads when the acceptance rules are expressed as RDF graph constraints."
msgstr ""

msgid "The graphs involved"
msgstr ""

msgid "Submitted RDF data graph"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"the submitter's parsed model. Most SPARQL ASK assertions should query this "
"graph."
msgstr ""

msgid "Shapes graph"
msgstr ""

msgid "the uploaded SHACL shapes that define the validation rules."
msgstr ""

msgid "Supplementary ontology graph"
msgstr ""

msgid "optional context for class and property inference."
msgstr ""

msgid "SHACL results graph"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"the validation report produced by SHACL. It contains result nodes with focus "
"nodes, source shapes, result paths, severities, and messages."
msgstr ""

msgid "SHACL result handling"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"This setting controls how normal SHACL validation results affect the step "
"outcome. It does not soften infrastructure failures: RDF parse errors, "
"invalid shapes, timeouts, and engine errors always fail the step immediately."
msgstr ""

msgid "Fail immediately on violations"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"stop after SHACL validation if the report contains any violation-level "
"result. Step assertions do not run."
msgstr ""

msgid "Fail after assertions"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"run SHACL first, then run the step assertions, then fail the step if SHACL "
"reported violations or any assertion failed. This is the recommended default."
msgstr ""

msgid "Report only"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"do not convert SHACL validation results into blocking findings. Counts and "
"the native report graph are still available, so SPARQL ASK, Basic, or CEL "
"assertions can decide exactly what should fail."
msgstr ""

msgid "SPARQL ASK target graphs"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"SHACL assertions use SPARQL ASK because it is the standard way to ask true/"
"false questions about RDF graphs."
msgstr ""

